{{Shinto Shrine | Name = Kaitō Shrine | image = [[File:IMG_kaido.JPG|250px]] | location = {{ill|Nagasaki Prefecture|ja|長崎県|12=draft}}, {{ill|Shinkamigotō|ja|新上五島町|12=draft}}, Arikawa-go | coordinates = {{Coord|32|59|12.2|N|129|06|51.2|E|scale:25000}} | Enshrined deity = {{ill|Kaitō no Kami|ja|海童神|12=draft}} | type = Former UnRanked Shrine (旧無格社) | Founded = Unknown | Main Hall = | Other Names = | Pilgrimage Sites = | festival = | Rituals = }}
'''Kaitō Shrine''' (海童神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|12=draft}} located on Ōgoshima in the Funatsu district of Arikawa-go, {{ill|Shinkamigotō|ja|新上五島町|12=draft}}, {{ill|Nagasaki Prefecture|ja|長崎県|12=draft}}. It is famous for its {{ill|torii|ja|鳥居|12=draft}} made from whale jawbones.
== Enshrined Deities == The main enshrined deity is {{ill|Kaitō no Kami|ja|海童神|12=draft}}, with {{ill|Hiruko|ja|蛭子神|12=draft}} also enshrined as an auxiliary deity.
The auxiliary deity Hiruko is the enshrined deity from the merged Funatsu Hiruko Shrine.
== History == [[File:IMG_kaido1.JPG|180px|thumb|Shrine on top of Ōgoshima]] [[File:IMG_kaido2.JPG|180px|thumb|Torii made from whale jawbones]]
The date of the shrine's founding is unknown. According to historical records from the town and {{ill|Nagasaki Prefecture|ja|長崎県|12=draft}}, it is said that between Genna 3 (1617) and Genna 5, drowning incidents frequently occurred among both adults and children swimming in the sea on June 17 each year in Arikawa Village. Following a divine message from Kaitō no Kami to the local official Takaira Fukuyemon, a stone shrine was built on Mikoshima to enshrine the deity.
The following year, during the festival on June 17, an improvised play called '''Niwaka Odori''' (にわかおどり) was performed, and no further drowning incidents occurred. This tradition continued annually and became the '''17th Day Festival''' (十七日祭り), a major event in Arikawa.
However, recent local historical research has identified inconsistencies in this account. Documents like the *Eguchi Manuscript*, detailing the village's fishing, agriculture, and customs from the mid-Edo period (18th century) to the early Meiji period (late 19th century), and records from {{ill|Arikawa Shrine|ja|有川神社|12=draft}} suggest the shrine's origins may date back to Keichō 3 (1598). During this time, a dragon god was enshrined as a protective deity on Nakano Island in Arikawa Bay, with the island named Ōgoshima in its honor.
Additionally, historical roles like "local official" (乙名役) and the figure Takaira Fukuyemon do not appear in records until Hōreki 5 (1755), indicating they likely did not exist at the shrine's purported founding time.
Records from 1864 indicate that the custom of processions known as '''Tōrimono''' (通りもの) began on June 17, 1752, to pray for maritime safety. The form of improvised performances known as '''Niwaka''' likely originated later, influenced by theatrical trends from Osaka, Kyoto, and Edo during the late Edo period.
In the mid-Meiji period, Funatsu Hiruko Shrine was merged with Kaitō Shrine. In 1908, it was further merged with {{ill|Arikawa Shrine|ja|有川神社|12=draft}}, during which the worship hall and torii were dismantled, leaving only the stone shrine. A new torii was built in 1927, and in 1973, a torii made from whale bones was donated by Nittō Whaling Co., Ltd. In 2004, land reclamation projects connected Ōgoshima to the mainland.
== Festivals == ;Major Festivals and Rituals * 17th Day Festival (July) * Fish Memorial Festival (August)
== Other Shrines == Other shrines in Arikawa-go include {{ill|Arikawa Shrine|ja|有川神社|12=draft}}. <gallery> File:Kami-goto.arikawa.JPG|Arikawa Shrine </gallery>
== References == * *Arikawa Town Local History* (1994), Arikawa Town Local History Compilation Committee * *The Truth and Myths of Arikawa's History*, by Fumio Araki, published in 2004 * *Arikawa Niwaka*, by Fumio Araki, published in 2007
